{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_roseheath_ver01/data/sn92070146/00414188837/1937110301/1062.xml":{"full_text":"[BUNGING\nALL THE KEW*\nTO IMPERIAL\n\u25bcALLEY\nWhat s Behind This\nBusiness Recession?\nIn the hands of a small group of con\ngressmen meeting at Washington Thurs\nday may lie the solution to the current\nbusiness recession throughout the United\nStates. The group, forming the house\nsub-committee on taxation, will study\nproposed revision of he federal tax on\nundeclared earnings, alon g with other\ntax measures.\nThe investing public largely com\nprised of business men who know how\nto keep a business alive and keep pay\nrolls and public spending ability going\n\u2014has been deeply concerned with the\nneed for tax revision, and especially for\nrevision of the tax on capital gains and\non corporation reserve funds. The theor\nists believed this tax would force corpor\nations to declare out more dividends,\nand thus increase spending power. This\nwas true for a while, but the after-effect\nwas worse than any morning-after head\nache.\nWhy?\nConcerns which wished to expand, ex\ntend their buildings and install new ma\nchinery obviously expected to bring\nabout these improvements through earn\nings. Just as obviously, these earnings\ncould not be accumulated in a week or\na month. It was necessary that they be\npiled up as \u201csurplus\u201d until there was\nenough to finance the development pro\njects.\nBut the tax law said, in effect, \u201cYou\ncannot do this. If you do, we\u2019ll tax you\nheavily. You must declare those earn\nings out as dividends!\u201d\nTo avoid the confiscatory tax penalty,\nbusiness had to lay aside its improve\nment program. It had to hand out the\nmoney almost as fast as it came in, to\navoid a heavy, taxable surplus.\nThe present tax setup places a high\npenalty on the establishment of reserves.\nThis was one of its purposes, but it has\nproved poor business. The recent down\nward flurry of business is, without\ndoubt, partially due to this cause.\nThere is another consideration, too.\nIf a firm is to guard against possible\nfuture depressions\u2014to forestall them,\nin fact\u2014it must lay up a reserve. With\nout a reserve, the first downward trend\nmeans discharge of employes, because\nthe employer will not be able to pay\nwages except from his income. The re\nsult will be added momentum for the\ndepression. Without reserves, the busi\nness man is helpless to prevent another\ndepression, because when the business\ncoming into his office slows down, his\nbusiness must slow down \u2014and the list\nof unemployed will grow.\nThe house sub-committee certainly\nshould consider revision of this law to\npermit business men to build up suffi\ncient reserves to act as a buffer against\nhard times, and especially to help tjiose\nsmaller corporations which find the\ntax burden a more serious penalty than\nit is to the monarchs of industry.\nWhen British Patience\nIs Exhausted\nThe speech of Foreign Secretary An\nthony Eden before the British House\nof Commons, in which he declared that\n\u2018\u2018We offer our cooperation to all, but we\naccept dictation from none,\u201d probably\nwill go down in history along with that\nother famous saying, \u201cEngland expects\nevery man to do his duty.\u201d It will be\ncome famous, we predict, because it is\nso seldom that the precedents of Brit\nish diplomacy permit patience to become\nso exhausted that such a phrase emerges.\nFor that reason, too, everyone inter\nested in the peace of the world sees in\nthe blunt declaration a warning and a\nthreat\u2014and hopes that Benio Mussolini,\nto whom the barbed words were directed,\nhas sense enough to see that there is a\ndifference between the diplomatic purr\nand the angry growl of the British Lion.\nOut Our Way by Williams\nTHAT AI NT FAIR!\nTH' SHOP FOOTBALL\nTEANA GITS TWO\nHOURS OFF EVERY\nPAY TO PRACTICE\nIMAGINE IT-*- GETTIKI\nPAID TO PLAY A\nCSAME\nit\nV\n'Ns\nAND ALL THEIR\nDOCTOR AMP\nHOSPITAL BILLS\nPAID WHUT\nLUXURY/\nA\nM.\n-I N\nft\n\u2022t\n\nft\nA\nm\nt\ns*\n\nJ\nI\nA\ni?.\ni\u00a9\na\nTHE LOAFERS.\n\u2022JT? \"n-k\nThoughts lor the Day\nAnd put no difference between us and them, puri\nfying their hearts by faith.\u2014Acts 15:9.\nNews Behind the News\nWanted A Building Boom\nWASHINGTON.\u2014Anyone who has an idea\nhow to start a building boom will kindly for\nward same to the White House.\nA secret call for suggestions recently went\nout to all spots in the federal set-up which\nhave been in any way concerned with housing.\nNumerous confidential reports have been or\nare being prepared. Experts in one agency\nwere told by a superior to submit all ideas they\nhad. whether the ideas seemed sound or not.\nBehind the President's sudden active inter\nest is a rather widespread belief among his\nadvisers that before long the country may need\na building boom or an armament program in\norder to -give a fillip to business and employ\nment. Few prefer ttie armament method.\nA secondary factor is the high cost of living.\nRents are rising and although this ordinarily\nwould cause a spurt in dwelling construction, no\nsuch effect is in sight because building costs\nalso have risen sharply. Rents threaten to\nadd even greater burdens to the H. C. L. be\ncause there's a huge national housing shortage.\nSecretary Ickes has cited figures indicating\nthat 5,500.000 new dwellings are \"needed.\u201d Other\nestimates say 750,000 new homes a year are\nneeded for replacement. Only 282.000 were built\nlast year and the number for this year will\nbe little if any higher.\nSubdued mumbling over high inflexible build\ning labor costs is audible again here in high\nplaces, with emphasis on the former. Raw\nmaterial prices have declined while building\nmaterial prices based thereon have gone up\nSuggestions as to what can be done about\nbuilding costs are usually vague.\nThere are proposals to cut the Federal\nHousing Administration\u2019s interest rate by one\nper cent and to raise its mortgage limit from\n80 to 90 per cent. Many authorities consider\nthese to be doubtful expedients.\nAnother proposal being carefully considered\nis to exempt from the capital gains tax persons\nwho would invest their otherwise taxable gains\nin housing.\nAn obviously desirable method of stimulat\ning a boom is to attract capital into limited divi\ndend housing corporations and the most realistic\nthinkers are trying to figure how. Primary ob\nstacle is the fact that people with money to\ninvest appear to be speculative-minded rather\nthan investment-minded.\nThe human animal shows a marked prefer\nence for profits of from 10 to 100 per cent when\noffered a safe, low return, longtime investment\nin housing. Authorities here say that com\nplete safety in limited dividend housing re\nquires a dividend limit of about 4 per cent,\nsince dwellings offering rents based on that\nrate are always sure to be occupied whereas\na rate of. say six per cent presents the risk of\nvacancies in any time of depression.\nSo the problem appears to be one of getting\nthe investing public and responsible promoters\ninterested in putting billions of dollars into this\nfour to six per cent market and leaving them\nlie.\nOther Editors Say\nBRUCE BARTON BREAKS A LANCE\n(Wail Street Journal)\nWhile the candidacy of Bruce Barton for\nCongress is local in the sense that those imme\ndiately concerned are confined to a small sec\ntion of New York City, the entry of this emi\nnently successful business man into the po\nlitical arena at this time has a national sig\nnificance. Other business men have gone into\npolitics, and other business men have run on a\nplatform promising the introduction of indus\ntrial efficiency into the tangled skein of gov\nempiental affairs. Few. however, have offered\nso definite a program and none has candidly\nentered the lists not to make laws, but to un\nmake legislation which is useless and worse.\n\u201cRepeal a Law a Day\u201d is more than a slogan.\nIt is a bona fide platform around which much\nof the thought of the country which is opposed\nto growing centralization of power can well\ncrystallize. Hitherto conservative criticism of\ncurrent trends in government has suffered from\nan inability to present a cohesive plan of action;\ntoward ending this condition tlje election of Mr.\nBarton will be an important step. It is not\nthat one congressman more or less, especially\na new one, can arrest the hitherto unstoppable\njuggernaut, but that his election can well serve\nas a beacon to encourage other reasonable\nmen, who have demonstrated their success in\nindustry, to enlist in the fight to take specific,\nconcrete action against the web of legislation\nin which the nation is at present struggling.\nOur interest in this candidacy is not that of\npromoting the fortunes of Mr. Barton who does\nnot need such a leg-up in any case, but in tak\ning at least one good, healthy chop at trhe\nGordian knot.\n\u201cNiagara river cave-dweller has Falls\nin his front yard.\u201d Still, certain Ohio\nans and Kentuckians have had the Ohio\nriver in their dining room.\nEditorials and Comment\nAll Chinese Look Alike to Me\nm\n\nV\n\nN\n'I?\nmm\nt\n|a,;,\n*>w\u00ab V .W\na\n\n\nV\nm\nt v\n\na\n\n\nw:\n\nI\n.5\niV\nX\ncr>\nA\n\n\njr)./\nfit\nFa\n\n<c\ni\n\u2022/y r&\n4w\n\n.-T\n*-ar\u00bb\n\nr\nA\n\n\nC:\nNew York Day by Day\nNEW YORK, Nov. 3.\u2014May and\nDecember romances in New York\nare acquiring a stability the young\ner folk muff. While the latter\nsplatter the news columns with\ndashes to Reno.j\nYouth and Age I\nare seen eyerty-1\nwhere fairly!\nbeaming a mari-|\ntal happiness.\nOne of the sea-j\nson\u2019s romantic]\nstressings of the]\ndisparity of ages|\nwas the wedding]\nof Ed Wynn and]\nFrieda Mie r s e.|\nShe is the tall]\nand stately show\ngirl type and was for several years\nin the Follies and Wynn\u2019s theatri\ncal enterprises. Wynn is 20 years\nthe senior of his bride.\nThey sailed away on his yacht\nas happy as a pair of love birds\nand returned to reside in the fash\nionable Park avenue section. George\nBlumenthal, the art collector, mar\nried a lady many years his junior\nand they are very happy. The same\nk true of the Sam Goldwyns.\nThe romance of Jimmy Walker\nand Betty Compton has, despite\nall predictions, been idyllic. And\nthe millionaire Jules Brulatour and\nthe much younger Hope Hampton\nare always together cooing like\nturtle doves. And this applies also\nto the Nicholas Schencks.\nSublime satire: The biggest\nchuckle in the play in which\nGeorge. M. Cohan impersonates the\npresident is during a cabinet meet\ning. The president suddenly turns\nto his attorney general and barks:\n\u201cCummnigs, take a law!\u201d\nUpper Park avenue is to have\na deluxe cheese shop, a miniature\nTaj Mahal dealing only in various\nbrands of cheese, domestic and\nforeign. For the past few years\nthe metropolis has been showing\na growing cheese consciousness. In\nthe finer restaurants the displays\non the portable tables are works\nof art. Many eating places, Hol\nland fashion, also list cheese on\nbreakfast menus. One of the pub\nlishing houses is readying a book\nto appeal solely to the cheese con\nnoisseurs. Bruno Lessing is an ex\npert cheeseist.\nThree havens for the stay-outs\nare Reuben's, Lindy\u2019s and Dave\u2019s\nBlue Room. They are the last stops\nin a night on the loose and where\nthe roysterers fortify themselves with\nham and eggs, onion soup or\nsteaming bowls of chili. Everybody\nis usually in a mellow mood when\nthey show up around 3 am. and\nNOTICE OF INTENTION TO EN\nGAGE IN THE SALE\nOF ALCOHOLIC\nBEVERAGES\nNov. 2. 1937\nTO WHOM IT MAY CONCERN:\nNotice is hereby Riven that fifteen\n\u2022days after the above date, the\nundersigned proposes to sell al\ncoholic beverages at these premises,\ndescribed as follows:\n460 Broadway. El Centro.\nPursuant to such intention, the\nundersigned is applying to the state\nBoard of Equalization for issuance\nof an alcoholic beverage license (or\nlicenses) for these premises as fol\nlows:\nOn Sale Beer.\nAnyone desiring to protest the\nissuance of such license <s) may\nfile a verified protest with the State\nBoaii of Equalization at Sacra\nmento. California, stating grounds\nfor denial as provided by law.\nLOUIS B TAGABAN.\nPEL G CUETO\nN 3\nWEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 3, 1937.\nlife goes along like a song. If there\nis a flare up of temper it doesn't\nlast long. The participants either\nwind up in tears or swing out in\na waltz.\nThe widely exploited \"No. 21\u201d,\nincidentlally, has decided to remain\nopen Sunday chiefly to serve what\nit calls a \u201chang-over breakfast\u201d\na menu calculated to startle the\njaded appetite into accepting a few\ntid-bits. The most famous of the\npick-me-up breakfasts used to be\nserved at Murray\u2019s on West 42nd\nstreet and was said to be the crea\ntion of the actor, John Mason. It\nconsisted first of chilled orange\njuice with a soupcon of brandy,\nthen two raw eggs doctored up\nwith Worcestershire sauce and\ndashes of paprika, then\u2014of all\nthings\u2014marinated herring. It was\na favorite of Nat Goodwin, Wilton\nLackaye and DeWolf Hopper when\nthe going was rough.\nO. O. Mc-rntyre\nI am told that gentlemen who\nhave had bad nights no longer re\nsort to the ancient formula, \u201ca bit\nof the hair of the dog that bit\nthem.\u201d Nowadadys they depend\nmostly on bromides but sometimes\n\u201ca bust in the arm\u201d, a needled\nBarbs\nEDWARD R STETTINIUS, JR.,\nwho graduated from college at 23\nand became a vice president of\nGeneral Motors shortly thereafter,\nis made chairman of U. S. Steel\nat 38\u2014proving what a young man\ncan accomplish by grit, perserver\nance and being the son of a Morg\nan partner.\nIf the nine-power conference\nMoesn\u2019t get going pretty soon, its\nfunctions as far as China is con\ncerned will strangely resemble\nthose of a coroner\u2019s jury.\nTire A P. of L. and C- I. O.\nhaving refused each other's de\nmands for unconditional surrender,\nthe next session of the \u201ccompro\nmise conference\" ought to be able\nto discuss actual compromise of\nfers.\nLooking Backward\nTHIRTY YEARS AGO\nNovember 3, 1907\nA committee consisting of W. E.\nWilsie, R H. Clark and W. H. Van\nHorn, have been appointed to be in\ncharge of the colt show to be held\nin El Centro the first week in Dec\nember.\nImperial Valley is getting in need\nof a chain gang. The county is\nbeing infested with hoboes and as\na result many thefts have\nbeen reported to the local police.\nTWENTY YEARS AGO\nNovember 3, 1937\nA thrift program, presented be\nfore the Wonen\u2019s Ten Thousand\nClub under the direction of Mrs.\nRay Edgar, proved intensely inter\nesting. Those taking part were:\nMesdames Roberts. Conley. Butter\nfield and Messrs. Shibley and Bou\ncher.\nFriends of Mr. and Mrs. O. B.\nTout are reminded that though the\nTouts have moved to a new home\ntheir telephone number remains\nthe same\nTEN YEARS AGO\nNovember 3, 1927\nFive warrants for the arrest of\ntraffic violators were Issued by\nJudge Perkins in the city court\nthis morning.\nThe warrants were issued upon\nfailure of the offenders to appear\nin court in answer to citations for\nminor violations.\nBy 0. 0. Mclntyre\ndrug, to carry them through the\ndistress of the morning after. But\nin the Manny Chappelle days they\nknew that the wine agent kept\nopen house at Rector\u2019s Sunday\nmorning .where all the bloods of\nthe town were welcome. Manny\u2019s\nrecipe was a chilled bottle of cham\npagne and heavily spiced raw oy\nsters. In extreme cases he suggest\ned an old-fashioned with a few\ndrops of absinthe. And in no time\nat all he had everybody singing\u2014\nand buying wine for all comers,\nwhich was, after all, the big idea.\nOne of the most amusing re\nmarks I ever heard was from the\nmumbling lips of a hang-over. It\nwas in the men\u2019s bar at the Ritz\nin Paris one sunny Easter morning\nWhen the whole city was on prom\nenade. Save for myself and white\naproned Frank and a figure\nsprawled over a table asleep, the\nbat was deserted. Finally the fig\nure, who had missed the boat, cast\na bleary look around and sighed:\n\u201cEaster, and not an egg in the\nhouse!\u2019 And tumbled back to his\nnap.\nYOU DON\u2019T HAVE\nTO BE RICH\nTO ENJOY RICH\nOLD HIKER\nP M\nim\n\nP\nm\nmm\n6\nBE\n<s*>\nV\nt m\n\nALSO HI HANDY\nPINT FLASKS\n90\nPROOF\nThere's A Barrel Of Quality\nIn Every Bottle, But It\nDoesn\u2019t Take A Barrel Of\nMoney To Buy It!\nAT the end of the \u201cper\nfeet day\u201d turn to\nsmoother, mellower OLD\nQUAKER. Aged two full\nyears in modern temper\nature controlled ware\nhouses ...OLD QUAKER\nis, in our opinion, the\nfinest, smoothest9o proof\nstraight whiskey on the\nAmerican market today.\nold QUAKER tastes bet\nter than ever, because\nits taste improves with\nage\u2014try OLD QUAKER\ntoday.\n11l\nSTRAIGHT 9Qj|IREO9 WHISKtY\nAlso available in Rye\nSTORED IN TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED WAREHOUSES\nCame. 1937-THE OLD QUAKER CO.-LAWRENCESURO, INDIANA\nFamous Sayings\nAs the flower is before tire fruit, so is faith before\ngood w\u2019orks,\u2014Whately.\nBruce Catton Says:\nObstacles in the Way of Boycott Plan\nOne of the most entertaining bits\nof business this winter ought to\nbe the attempt to persuade the\nAmerican women to stop wearing\nsilk stockings in order that the vil\nlainous Japanese may be foiled of\ntheir designs on China.\nProm the shapely legs of Ameri\ncans to the muddy battlefields of\nShanghai may seem like a long\njump. But there is a connection,\nspelled simply in one word: boy\ncott.\nThe argument runs something\nlike this.\nJapan is making war on China\nin plain violation of all existing\ntreaties. If one nation can treat\nanother nation so, no nation is\nsafe from the threat of force; Am\nerica, accordingly, must do her\npart to restrain the Japanese.\nBut the Japanese don\u2019t restrain\neasily. They have, in fact, shrug\nFactographs\nThe U. S. treasury department\nissued the first small-size green\nbacks eight years ago, calling for\nredemption of the larger bills.\nDespite repeated calls since then,\nmore than $250,000,000 in old bills\nare still out.\nThe largest public office building\nin the world is the U. S. depart\nment of agriculture structure in\nWashingon, D. C. It contains\n4.500 rooms, seven miles of corri\ndors. and 39 elevators.\n\nFollowing the outbreak of the\nSino-Japanese conflict, Tokio\u2019s 73.-\n000 geisha girls discarded their\ntraditional colorful garb for drab\nclothes.\nSince 1910 there has been a 50\nper cent increase in the number of\nbusiness and professional women\nin the United States.\nPullman car construction was\nrevolutionized in 1907 when the\nfirst all-steel Pullman was built-\nHippocrates, called the \u201cFather\nof Medicine\u201d, built a temple for\nsun-bathers 2.400 years ago.\nSunshine increases both the iron\nand iodine content of the body.\nThe Grab Bag\nOne-Minute Test\nWho is U. S. ambassador to\nJapan\n2. What three languages are\nspoken in Belgium?\n3. Name the capital of Missouri.\nHints on Etiquette\nIt is not considered good taste to\nindulge in a highly technical dis\ncussion when in mixed company.\nToday\u2019s Horoscope\nMost persons whose birthday oc\ncurs today are deep thinkers. They\nlike to probe beneath the surface\nof things and acquire obscure\nknowledge.\nWords of Wisdom\nEvery man\u2019s task is his life pre\nserver. \u2014Franklin.\nOne-Minute Test Answers\n1. Joseph C. Grew of New Hamp\nshire.\n2. French, Flemish and German.\n3. Jefferson City.\nged off all protests. And no Am\nerican cares to see his country go\nto war to make protests effective.\nThere remains, then, only the boy\ncott. If all lovers of peace and\ngood will will stop buying Japanese\ngoods, the Japanese will see the\nerror of their ways and the dove\nof peace will flutter once more\nover war-racked China.\nWhich brings us back to silk\nstockings.\nJapan's principal export to this\ncountry is silk. If we are going to\nboycott Japan, we have got to stop\nbuying silk. And if we are going\nto stop buying silk, we have some\nhow got to persuade the American\nwoman to encase her nether limbs\nin something besides silk stockings\n\u2014in lisle, in rayon, or perhaps In\nthe plain old-time cotton article.\nAnd that, when you stop to think\nabout it, Is going to be something\nof a job. Never has there been a\ncountry as leg conscious as modern\nAmerica. The American woman,\nyou might say, struggled for gen\nerations to win recognition of her\nright to wear silk hose day in and\nday out, regardless of her station\nIn life. Anyone who imagines\nthat she is readily going to surren\nder that right, even for a noble and\naltruistic cause, may well have an\nother guess coming.\nAll of which compels one to won\nder just how effective these inter\nnational boycotts talked of so\nfreely, these days\u2014are ever going\nto be.\nThere seems to be a school of\nthought which would sig>stitu#,e\nthe boycott for war, which would\nmake it a padded club by which an\nerring nation may be clubbed back\ninto good behavior. On paper it\nis all very simple. In actual prac\ntice it may be quite different.\nFor we buy goods in interna\ntional trade, not because we ad\nmire the people who make them,\nbut because we like to have the\ngoods. It is going to take deep and\nstrong emotion to make such boy\ncotts successful. Is our desire to\nsee Japan restrained, for instance,\nquite as sincere and universal as\nour wish to have the American\nwoman continue to wear silk hose?\nMaybe it is. If so, watch out,\nJapan. But then again, maybe it\nisn\u2019t.\nDR. GOBLE HURST\nCHIROPRACTOR\nKin. 246 Professional Bldg.\nELECTROTHERAPY\nPHYSIOTHERAPY\nPhone 75-J\nEL CENTRO GETS\nRID OF CORNS\nIn the past three weeks thousands\nof El Centro men and women have\nended their corn and callous trou\nbles with END-O-CORN. No mat\nter how many so-called \u2018\u2018corn\ncures\" you have tried, if you stilt\nhave your corns go to The Valley\nDrug Co., or any otrer GOOD Drug\nStore and get END-O-CORN. Use\ntonight, Tomorrow all right. It\ncannot fail. How many times have\nyou said, \u201cI\u2019d give $lO to get rid of\nthat pesky corn?\" END-O-CORN is\nworth $5O, but costs only 50c.\nEND-O-CORN","height":"29316","width":"23120"}}
